[Patient] How much water should I drink daily to manage my heart failure?
[Educator] Aim for 6-8 cups a day, but monitor your weight and symptoms for changes.
[Patient] Can I drink any fluids or just water?
[Educator] Limit fluids high in sodium like soda and opt for water, herbal tea, or low-sodium broth.
[Patient] How do I know if I'm drinking too much or too little?
[Educator] Track your fluid intake and output. If you gain weight suddenly, feel short of breath, or have swelling, contact me.
[Patient] Are there foods I should avoid that can make my heart failure worse?
[Educator] Avoid processed foods, canned soups, and salty snacks. Opt for fresh fruits, vegetables, and lean proteins.
[Patient] Can I have a cheat day or indulge in my favorite salty snacks occasionally?
[Educator] It's best to limit salty treats to special occasions. Try finding healthier alternatives to satisfy cravings.
[Patient] How can I afford to buy healthy food on a tight budget?
[Educator] Look into local food banks or community programs that offer affordable fresh produce. Prioritize nutrient-dense foods.
[Patient] Is it okay to drink more water if I'm feeling thirsty?
[Educator] Listen to your body, but try to stick to the recommended fluid intake. Monitor for any changes in symptoms.
[Patient] How do I know if I'm retaining too much fluid?
[Educator] Pay attention to sudden weight gain, swelling in your legs or abdomen, and increased shortness of breath.
[Patient] Can I drink caffeinated beverages like coffee or tea?
[Educator] Limit caffeine intake as it can affect your heart rate and blood pressure. Opt for decaffeinated options instead.